<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-07-09T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-07-09T16:00:00-05:00" n="929" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d929">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">823.00 Revolutions/327: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Peru</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BWC1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Burdett</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-07-09T16:00:00-05:00">July 9,
                                    1932—4 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received 6:14 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>100. Regarding cable advice Chief of U. S. Navy Mission today to Naval
                            Intelligence concerning Peruvian request for naval air bombs from
                            Panama, this would strengthen position of the Naval Mission but
                            revolutionary movement can be suppressed without air bombardment and
                            native aviators would probably kill helpless noncombatants. Embassy
                            suggests that approval of the Department be deferred until the
                            revolutionary movement in Peru is over which will probably be very
                            soon.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_BWC1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Burdett</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>